07526nam a22009495i 9780812296723DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122967237 a10.9783/97808122967232doi  a(DE-B1597)531779  a(OCoLC)1153084056  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ76.8.U5bB47 2020 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a306.76/6097322300aBeyond the Politics of the Closet :bGay Rights and the American State Since the 1970s /ced. by Jonathan Bell. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Privilege, Power, and Activism in Gay Rights Politics Since the 1970s -- tPart I. Public Policy Comes Out The 1970s -- t1. A Clinic Comes Out: Idealism, Pragmatism, and Gay Health Services in Boston, 1971–1985 -- t2. “A Ray of Sunshine”: Housing, Family, and Gay Political Power in 1970s Los Angeles -- t3. Making Sexual Citizens: LGBT Politics, Health Care, and the State in the 1970s -- tPart II. Confronting AIDS -- t4. AIDS and the Urban Crisis: Stigma, Cost, and the Persistence of Racism in Chicago, 1981–1996 -- t5. “Don’t We Die Too?”: The Politics of AIDS and Race in Philadelphia -- t6. Black Gay Lives Matter: Mobilizing Sexual Identities in the Eras of Reagan and Thatcher Conservatism -- tPart III. Beyond Liberalism and Conservatism -- t7. Gay and Conservative: An Early History of the Log Cabin Republicans -- t8. “No Discrimination & No Special Rights”: Gay Rights, Family Values, and the Politics of Moderation in the 1992 Election -- t9. Homophobia Baiting: Queering the Trayvon Martin Archives and Challenging the AntiBlackness of Color-Blind Politics -- tNOTES -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the 1970s, queer Americans demanded access not only to health and social services but also to mainstream Democratic and Republican Party politics. The AIDS crisis of the 1980s made the battles for access to welfare, health care, and social services for HIV-positive Americans, many of them gay men, a critically important story in the changing relationship between sexual minorities and the government. The 1980s and 1990s marked a period in which religious right attacks on the civil rights of minorities, including LGBT people, offered opportunities for activists to create campaigns that could mobilize a base in mainstream politics and contribute to the gradual legitimization of sexual minorities in American society.Beyond the Politics of the Closet features essays by historians whose work on LGBT history delves into the decades between the mid-1970s and the millennium, a period in which the relationship between activist networks, the state, capitalism, and political parties became infinitely more complicated. Examining the crucial relationship between sexuality, race, and class, the volume highlights the impact gay rights politics and activism have had on the wider American political landscape since the rights revolutions of the 1960s.The three sections of Beyond the Politics of the Closet conceptualize LGBT politics both chronologically and thematically. The first section highlights the ways in which the immediate post-rights revolution period created new demands on the part of sexual minorities for social services, especially in health and housing. The second examines the impact of the AIDS crises on different aspects of national and local LGBT politics. The last section considers how analyzing LGBT politics can reorient our understanding of "the closet" and illuminate the challenges for those seeking to integrate questions of sexual rights into broader political narratives, whether of the left or the right.Contributors: Ian M. Baldwin, Catherine Batza, Jonathan Bell, Julio Capo, Jr., Rachel Guberman, Clayton Howard, Kevin Mumford, Dan Royles, Timothy Stewart-Winter  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aGay liberation movementxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aGay liberation movementzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aGay rightszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aGay Studies.  aGender Studies.  aLesbian Studies.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.  aQueer Studies.1 aBaldwin, Ian M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatza, Katie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCapó, Julio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuberman, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoward, Clayton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMumford, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoyles, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStewart-Winter, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUPP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069044640